<li id="cite_note-146"><b><a href="#cite_ref-146" title="">^</a></b> Gimarc, George, <i>Punk Diary</i>, p. 145. Gimarc refers to sources claiming that the "My Way" recording involved no contact between Vicious and the Jones-Cook duo; Temple, however, says that Jones was flown over to Paris to join Vicious in the studio (Temple, Julian, "Commentary", 1:29:18–1:29:20), and seems to indicate that he recorded his guitar part there (1:33:09–1:33:16).</li>
<li id="cite_note-147"><b><a href="#cite_ref-147" title="">^</a></b> Savage, Jon, <i>England's Dreaming</i>, p. 497–498. Savage describes the single as being a double A-side; other sources indicate that the Biggs vocal was the A-side and the Vicious vocal the B-side (e.g., Gimarc, George, <i>Punk Diary</i>, p. 145). There is no disagreement that the Vicious side was the more popular.</li>
